This is not a bug. It is, however, a common pitfall for users who are new to Vue – especially those with an Angular background.

When Vue initializes, it [adds reactive getters and setters][1] to each property in the Vue instance&#39;s `data` object. However, Vue cannot setup reactive getters and setters for properties that don&#39;t exist. 

If you want a property to be reactive, it must be initialized with a default value:

```
var app = new Vue({
    el: &#39;#app&#39;,
    data: {
        car: {
            make: &#39;&#39;,
            year: &#39;&#39;
        }
    }
});
```


  [1]: https://vuejs.org/v2/guide/reactivity.html

To make your first example reactive, data property needs to have getter and setter. You can read about it [here][1].

In short example if your data looks like that:
```
data() {
  return {
    car: {
      make: &#39;&#39;,
    },
  },
},
```
and you want to add property `year` as reactive data you need to set it some where (in mounted hook for example)
```
mounted() {
  this.$set(this.car, &#39;year&#39;, 2012)
},
```
[working example][2]


But to be honest when you know what properties you need then add them to your data at the start.

```
data() {
  return {
    car: {
      make: &#39;&#39;,
      year: &#39;&#39;,
    },
  },
},
```


  [1]: https://vuejs.org/v2/guide/reactivity.html
  [2]: https://jsbin.com/cebozaniyi/1/edit?html,js,output

